ce:section.ce:para:
XPS was employed to investigate the composition and valence state of the different nitrogen doping content of nitrogen-doped CQDs. Fig. 5
                      shows the full XPS spectra of the LN-CQDs, MN-CQDs, and HN-CQDs composed of C, O, and N elements, demonstrating that both contained the same elemental compositions. In addition, the weight ratio of nitrogen elements changed from 3.10 % to 6.84 %–10.45 %, indicating that the increased nitrogen content and synthesized samples were consistent with the initial design expectations. The C 1s spectra were fitted into three types of C species sp2 C (CC/C–C) at 284.4 eV, sp3 C (C–O/C–N) at 286.4 eV, and –CO at 288.4 eV [27]. Compared to the LN-CQDs, the HN-CQDs exhibited a higher content of CC/C–C and C–N, as well as a lower content of CO, indicating that in the HN-CQDs, nitrogen groups contained partially substituted oxygen-containing groups. For N 1s, the XPS spectra could be converted into pyridinic N (399.8 eV) and graphite N (401.4 eV) [27]. Despite the results showing that graphite nitrogen content in LN-CQD was the highest (Table 1
                     ), which suggested that the dominant form of nitrogen doping in nitrogen-doped CQDs varies with changes in the nitrogen content, a more detailed calculation was required to determine the overall graphitic nitrogen content in all samples. Considering the known weight ratios of nitrogen in the three types of CQDs through full XPS spectra, detailed calculations confirmed that the total graphitic nitrogen content in HN-CQD was the highest (10.45 %*30.07 % > 6.84 %*38.89 % > 3.1 %*58.83 %). The presence of graphitic nitrogen implied that more nitrogen atoms entered the aromatic carbon core structure. This could be attributed to the nucleophilic ring-opening reactions between graphitic nitrogen and the epoxy groups on the surfaces of the aromatic structures, leading to the integration of nitrogen into the aromatic carbon core. These chemical interactions resulted in the replacement of a substantial number of central carbon atoms by nitrogen atoms, with nitrogen doping introducing mid-gap states into the π-conjugated system. This significantly disrupted its integrity and diminished the material's chemical reactivity [28]. Moreover, the HN-CQDs rich in pyridinic nitrogen exhibited increased chemical reactivity.
